Hello Michel,

On Thu, 2005-09-01 at 21:07 +0200, Michel Vincent wrote:
> I have a MacMini with Mac OS X, and a Samsung display, without any 
> button to adjust brightness and contrast. As MagicTune provided by 
> Samsung does not work on Mac OS, I use DDCcontrol. I boot on Linux 
> using a liveCD of Ubuntu, and I run DDCControl. Congratulation  for 
> this program which works very well.

Thanks .-)

> Even though I do not adjust my display very often, the whole process is 
> quite long, and I am wondering whether it could be possible to use 
> DDCcontrol directly on Mac OS X.
> 
> The graphic card of the MacMini is an ATI Radeon, and the documentation 
> says that there is no PCI access, so that pci-utils is not necessary. 
> But the person who compiled DDCcontrol for me (a contributor from the 
> discussion forum of MacBidouille,  who helped me a lot, as I am new to 
> Linux) told me that it was impossible to compile without pciutils-dev. 

I don't think so, I think that if you configure ddccontrol with
"--disable-ddcpci" flag, it won't need pciutils.

> And pci-utils is not present on Mac OS (as far as I understood).

As pci-utils is not available on MacOS, you lose PCI access. The other
way of accessing the I2C bus of the graphics cards are the *Linux*
kernel drivers. So it won't work with the current ddccontrol.

It is possible to access these I2C busses on Mac OS X (Mitsubishi did it
with their control tool for Mac), but I don't have enough knowledge of
this system, and don't have Apple hardware, so it is not possible for me
to help you.

> I hope that my question is understandable, as I am really not a 
> specialist of the subject. And sorry if I am a little bit out of the 
> scope, as I do not really use Linux.

No you aren't out of scope, Mac OS X support would be interesting.

Meilleures salutations,

Nicolas



